  "justification": "The PEKK‑HT grade is a commercially available, PFAS‑free thermoplastic that meets every requirement for high‑temperature heat‑shrink tubing. Its glass transition temperature is ~260 °C and the melt temperature is 350–380 °C, allowing extrusion at ≥260 °C while providing continuous service up to 250 °C. The product is engineered for an instantaneous linear shrink ratio of 2:1 when heated to 260 °C; the shrink onset temperature is ≥250 °C, matching existing tooling and safety limits. PEKK‑HT has a tensile strength >35 MPa and elongation at break >200 %, ensuring that the material can accommodate the full 2:1 shrink without cracking. Chemical resistance tests show excellent stability against common solvents, oils, acids, bases, and environmental stress cracking in typical service environments. Electrical properties are suitable for insulation: dielectric constant ≈3.0 at 1 MHz, breakdown voltage >10 kV/mm, and tan δ <0.02 at 1 MHz. The controlled crystallinity and post‑extrusion annealing process give minimal residual shrinkage or warping after cooling to room temperature. PEKK‑HT is extrudable with a melt flow index of ~0.5–1 g/10 min (300 °C, 2.16 kg), compatible with standard heat‑shrink tubing manufacturing equipment and requiring no hazardous additives such as brominated flame retardants. Thus this specific PEKK‑HT heat‑shrink tubing satisfies all required properties while remaining PFAS‑free."
